\section{Materials and Methods}

\subsection{Study design and data resources}
This study comprehensively evaluated the expression profile, clinical relevance, prognostic value, functional networks, DNA methylation characteristics, and immune associations of \textit{ACTL8} in uterine corpus endometrial carcinoma (UCEC) using publicly available multi-omics datasets and established online bioinformatics platforms. The main data sources and tools included The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA-UCEC), GEO (GSE106191), UALCAN, TISIDB, Kaplan--Meier Plotter, LinkedOmics, STRING, MethSurv, PathCards, and Xiantao Academic. Unless otherwise specified, statistical significance was defined as a two-sided $p < 0.05$.

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} expression in UCEC and non-malignant tissues}
To compare \textit{ACTL8} mRNA expression between endometrial cancer and non-malignant tissues, the GEO dataset GSE106191 (endometrial cancer vs endometrial hyperplasia) was downloaded from the Gene Expression Omnibus (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/). Data visualization was performed using the R package \texttt{ggplot2} (v3.3.6), and statistical testing was performed using \texttt{stats} (v4.2.1) and \texttt{car} (v3.1-0). TCGA-derived transcriptomic comparisons between UCEC and normal/adjacent normal tissues were obtained through Xiantao Academic and/or UALCAN (http://ualcan.path.uab.edu/), depending on platform availability. 

To assess protein-level expression, \textit{ACTL8} protein abundance in UCEC and normal endometrium was queried from UALCAN, which provides CPTAC/TCGA-based proteomic summaries.

\subsection{Association between \textit{ACTL8} expression and clinicopathological characteristics}
Associations between \textit{ACTL8} expression and clinical features in UCEC were investigated using multiple complementary resources. First, the ``Clinical'' and ``Subtype'' modules of TISIDB (http://cis.hku.hk/TISIDB/) were used to evaluate the relationships between \textit{ACTL8} expression and clinical stage, tumor grade, molecular subtype, and immune subtype.

Second, detailed stratified comparisons across clinical variables were performed using Xiantao Academic (https://www.xiantao.love/), which integrates TCGA RNA-seq and clinical annotations. TCGA level 3 HTSeq-FPKM expression data were converted to transcripts per million (TPM) and log$_2$-transformed prior to analysis. Normality was assessed by the Shapiro--Wilk test. Group comparisons were conducted using the Wilcoxon rank-sum test (two groups) or Kruskal--Wallis test (multiple groups), followed by Dunn's post hoc test with Bonferroni correction when appropriate. To validate major findings, UALCAN stratified analyses were also performed for selected clinicopathologic variables.

\subsection{Diagnostic performance and survival analyses}
The diagnostic ability of \textit{ACTL8} to distinguish UCEC from non-malignant samples was evaluated by receiver operating characteristic (ROC) analysis using Xiantao Academic. ROC curves and the area under the curve (AUC) were computed with the R package \texttt{pROC} (v1.18.0) and visualized with \texttt{ggplot2}.

Survival analyses were conducted to assess the association between \textit{ACTL8} expression and overall survival (OS), recurrence-free survival (RFS), disease-specific survival (DSS), and progression-free interval (PFI). Kaplan--Meier Plotter (http://kmplot.com/analysis/) and Xiantao Academic were used to generate Kaplan--Meier curves. Patients were dichotomized into high- and low-expression groups using the median \textit{ACTL8} expression as the cut-point. The log-rank test was used to compare survival curves. Cox proportional hazards regression was applied where available. Subgroup survival analyses were further performed within clinical strata (e.g., stage, grade, histologic subtype, invasion depth, menopause status, diabetes status, and therapy-related variables) using Xiantao Academic.

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} co-expression network and functional enrichment analyses}
To characterize genes co-expressed with \textit{ACTL8} in UCEC, the LinkedOmics database (http://linkedomics.org/) was used. The LinkFinder module identified \textit{ACTL8}-associated genes in TCGA-UCEC using Pearson correlation. Results were displayed as volcano plots, heatmaps, and scatter plots. The LinkInterpreter module performed gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) for Gene Ontology biological process (GO\_BP), cellular component (GO\_CC), molecular function (GO\_MF), and Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) pathways. Enrichment significance was evaluated using the false discovery rate (FDR), and FDR $\leq 0.05$ was considered significant.

To identify experimentally supported \textit{ACTL8}-interacting proteins, STRING (https://cn.string-db.org/) was queried. The overlap between STRING-derived binding partners and LinkedOmics co-expressed genes was computed using an online Venn diagram tool (https://bioinformatics.psb.ugent.be/webtools/Venn/).

To support pathway-level interpretation, genes in the cell-cycle pathway network were obtained from PathCards (https://pathcards.genecards.org/), and correlations between \textit{ACTL8} and cell-cycle-related genes were visualized using the ``Single gene coexpression heat map'' function in Xiantao Academic.

\subsection{DNA methylation analysis and prognostic relevance of CpG sites}
To explore epigenetic features of \textit{ACTL8}, promoter methylation levels were examined using UALCAN, including comparisons between normal and tumor tissues and stratification by tumor grade when available.

To assess CpG-site-specific prognostic significance, MethSurv (https://biit.cs.ut.ee/methsurv/) was used to analyze TCGA-UCEC methylation data. MethSurv fits Cox proportional hazards models to estimate hazard ratios (HRs) with 95\% confidence intervals (CIs) for overall survival (OS) based on CpG methylation levels. Patients were dichotomized into high- and low-methylation groups using MethSurv's automatically selected best cut-point (e.g., mean, median, or quantile-based split). Likelihood-ratio test $p$ values and proportional hazards (PH) assumption tests were recorded. CpG sites with $p < 0.05$ were considered prognostically significant.

\subsection{Immune infiltration and immune checkpoint correlation analyses}
The relationships between \textit{ACTL8} expression and immune contexture in UCEC were assessed using Xiantao Academic and TISIDB. Spearman correlation was used to evaluate associations between \textit{ACTL8} expression and estimated infiltration levels of immune cell subsets. Spearman correlation was also used to assess expression relationships between \textit{ACTL8} and immune checkpoint-related genes. Differences in immune cell enrichment scores between \textit{ACTL8}-high and \textit{ACTL8}-low groups were tested using the Wilcoxon rank-sum test.

\subsection{Statistical analysis}
All analyses were performed using R (v4.2.1) and integrated web-based tools as described above. Continuous variables were compared using parametric tests (paired/independent-sample $t$ test, Welch one-way ANOVA with Games--Howell post hoc test) or nonparametric tests (Wilcoxon rank-sum, Kruskal--Wallis with Dunn's post hoc test) according to distribution and group structure. Correlation analyses used Pearson or Spearman methods as appropriate. Survival analyses used Kaplan--Meier curves with log-rank tests and Cox regression. Multiple-testing correction followed platform defaults (e.g., LinkedOmics FDR) or Bonferroni adjustment when explicitly applied. Statistical significance was set at $p < 0.05$.

\section{Results}

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} is upregulated in UCEC at both mRNA and protein levels}
\textit{ACTL8} expression was consistently increased in UCEC across multiple datasets. TCGA-based analyses showed significantly higher \textit{ACTL8} mRNA expression in UCEC tissues compared with normal endometrial tissues (Fig.~\ref{fig1}A,B). Paired analyses further confirmed that \textit{ACTL8} expression was elevated in tumor samples relative to matched adjacent normal tissues (Fig.~\ref{fig1}C). In the GEO dataset GSE106191, \textit{ACTL8} expression was significantly higher in endometrial cancer tissues than in endometrial hyperplasia tissues (Fig.~\ref{fig1}D, $p < 0.05$). Consistently, UALCAN analyses demonstrated increased \textit{ACTL8} mRNA and protein abundance in UCEC (Fig.~\ref{fig1}E--H).

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} expression is associated with adverse clinicopathological features in UCEC}
To explore clinical relevance, we evaluated \textit{ACTL8} expression across multiple clinicopathologic strata. Xiantao Academic analyses revealed that higher \textit{ACTL8} expression was associated with advanced clinical stage (stage III/IV), older age ($>60$ years), serous histological type, higher histologic grade (G2/G3), and deeper tumor invasion ($\geq 50\%$) (Fig.~\ref{fig2}A--L). Stratified analyses in UALCAN further supported significant differences in \textit{ACTL8} expression across selected characteristics, including weight, tumor grade, and tumor history (Fig.~\ref{fig3}A--M).

\subsection{Diagnostic and prognostic value of \textit{ACTL8} in UCEC}
ROC analysis indicated that \textit{ACTL8} had modest diagnostic performance for distinguishing UCEC from non-malignant samples (AUC = 0.62; Fig.~\ref{fig4}A). 

Survival analyses consistently demonstrated an unfavorable prognostic association of high \textit{ACTL8} expression. Kaplan--Meier Plotter analyses showed that elevated \textit{ACTL8} expression was significantly associated with poorer OS and RFS (Fig.~\ref{fig4}B,C). TCGA-based analyses using Xiantao Academic further indicated that high \textit{ACTL8} expression predicted shorter OS, DSS, and PFI (Fig.~\ref{fig4}D--F) (all $p < 0.05$). 

Subgroup survival analyses suggested that the prognostic impact of \textit{ACTL8} was broadly observed across multiple clinical strata. High \textit{ACTL8} expression was associated with poorer OS in most evaluated subgroups, including White race, stage III disease, complete response (CR) after primary therapy, both age groups ($\leq 60$ and $>60$), BMI $>30$, endometrioid histology, no residual tumor (R0), grade G3, both invasion groups ($<50\%$ and $\geq 50\%$), postmenopausal status, diabetes status, hormone therapy status, radiation therapy status, and anthropometric subgroups (Fig.~\ref{fig5}). Similar patterns were observed for DSS (Fig.~\ref{fig6}) and PFI (Fig.~\ref{fig7}), supporting the robustness of the association between high \textit{ACTL8} expression and unfavorable outcomes in UCEC.

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} co-expression network suggests involvement in proliferation-related programs}
LinkedOmics co-expression analysis identified widespread transcriptional correlations with \textit{ACTL8} in TCGA-UCEC. A total of 10{,}511 genes were significantly positively correlated with \textit{ACTL8}, whereas 9{,}387 genes were significantly negatively correlated (Fig.~\ref{fig8}A; FDR = 1.00E$-$11). The top 50 positively and negatively correlated genes are shown in heatmaps (Fig.~\ref{fig9}A,C), and representative top correlations are shown by scatter plots (Fig.~\ref{fig9}B,D). Among the most strongly correlated genes were \textit{GAB4} ($r=0.543$), \textit{TPX2} ($r=0.492$), \textit{TTX} ($r=0.487$), \textit{FAM46C} ($r=-0.486$), \textit{TRIP13} ($r=0.480$), and \textit{DUSP9} ($r=0.478$), with corresponding statistical significance as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig9}.

GSEA performed in LinkedOmics indicated that \textit{ACTL8}-associated genes were enriched in GO terms and KEGG pathways related to tumor-associated biological functions (Fig.~\ref{fig10}, FDR $\leq 0.05$). In addition, pathway-level correlation analysis demonstrated coordinated expression between \textit{ACTL8} and genes within the cell-cycle pathway network (Fig.~\ref{fig11}), supporting a potential association between \textit{ACTL8} expression and proliferative signaling in UCEC.

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} CpG methylation is associated with prognosis in UCEC}
To investigate whether epigenetic alterations of \textit{ACTL8} are linked to clinical outcomes in UCEC, we performed CpG-site-specific survival analyses using the MethSurv database based on TCGA-UCEC methylation profiles. Among the evaluated CpG loci annotated to \textit{ACTL8}, two CpG sites showed statistically significant associations with overall survival (OS).

Specifically, methylation at cg03220543 (annotated to the 5$'$UTR region of \textit{ACTL8}; Open Sea) was significantly associated with OS (HR = 2.864, 95\% CI 1.778--4.614, $p = 1.52 \times 10^{-5}$; likelihood-ratio test $p = 9.46 \times 10^{-6}$). In addition, methylation at cg09821328 (located in the gene body; N Shore) was also associated with OS (HR = 1.955, 95\% CI 1.209--3.160, $p = 0.00622$; likelihood-ratio test $p = 0.00819$). For both CpG sites, proportional hazards assumption tests were not significant (PH test $p = 0.979$ for cg03220543 and $p = 0.885$ for cg09821328), supporting the applicability of the Cox proportional hazards model. These results indicate that methylation of specific CpG loci within \textit{ACTL8} is prognostically informative in UCEC (Fig.~\ref{fig12}).

\subsection{\textit{ACTL8} expression correlates with immune infiltration and immune checkpoint-related genes}
To assess the relationship between \textit{ACTL8} and the tumor immune microenvironment, we analyzed correlations between \textit{ACTL8} expression and immune cell infiltration estimates in TCGA-UCEC using Xiantao Academic. \textit{ACTL8} expression showed significant correlations with the inferred infiltration levels of multiple immune cell subsets (Fig.~\ref{fig13}A--T). Moreover, \textit{ACTL8} expression was significantly correlated with the expression of immune checkpoint-related genes (Fig.~\ref{fig13}U), suggesting that \textit{ACTL8} may reflect differences in immune contexture in UCEC.
